Oh boy, what a thrilling question! In Java, the keyword you're thinking of is... *dramatic pause* ...not "isn't there some way to differentiate between an object's variable and a local method variable?" Because, you know, that would be super intuitive and clear.

But no, in all seriousness (or rather, sarcasm), Java has a neat trick up its sleeve called "shadowing." When you declare a local variable with the same name as a field in an enclosing class or interface, the local variable shadows the field. So, if you want to access the field, you'll need to use the `this` keyword. For example:

```java
public class Example {
    private String name;

    public void someMethod(String name) {
        // This is the local variable
        System.out.println(name);  // prints the parameter

        // To refer to the instance variable, use 'this'
        System.out.println(this.name);  // prints the field
    }
}
```

